  </entry>
  
  <entry>
    <title>Principal component analysis</title>
    <link href="https://xgdong.github.io/2019/09/16/Principal-component-analysis/"/>
    <id>https://xgdong.github.io/2019/09/16/Principal-component-analysis/</id>
    <published>2019-09-16T14:03:23.000Z</published>
    <updated>2019-09-19T06:39:43.343Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><strong>Principal component analysis (PCA)</strong> is a statistical procedure that uses an orthogonal transformation to convert a set of observations of possibly correlated variables (entities each of which takes on various numerical values) into a set of values of linearly uncorrelated variables called principal components.   </p><a id="more"></a><p>Principal components analysis is a powerful approach for correcting for stratification in genome-wide association studies. This document provides the pipeline of three methods for principal component analysis using genomic data. </p><ul><li><p><strong>Pipeline</strong></p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br><span class="line">12</span><br><span class="line">13</span><br><span class="line">14</span><br><span class="line">15</span><br><span class="line">16</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">#qc</span><br><span class="line">plink --tfile &lt;file&gt; --allow-extra-chr --chr-set 33 --geno 0.1 --hwe 0.0000001 --maf 0.01  --mind 0.1 --make-bed --out &lt;file&gt;_qc</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">plink --bfile &lt;file&gt;_qc --chr-set 33 --allow-extra-chr --indep-pairwise 100 25 0.25</span><br><span class="line">plink --bfile &lt;file&gt;_qc --chr-set 33 --allow-extra-chr --extract plink.prune.in --make-bed --out &lt;file&gt;_qc.prune</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">##gcta PCA</span><br><span class="line">gcta64 --bfile &lt;file&gt;_qc.prune --autosome --autosome-num 33 --make-grm --out &lt;file&gt;_qc</span><br><span class="line">gcta64 --grm &lt;file&gt;_qc --pca 20 --out &lt;file&gt;_qc</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">##Plink MDS</span><br><span class="line">plink --bfile &lt;file&gt;_qc.prune --chr-set 38 --allow-extra-chr --genome</span><br><span class="line">plink --bfile &lt;file&gt;_qc --chr-set 38 --allow-extra-chr --read-genome plink.genome --cluster --mds-plot 10 </span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">##smartPCA</span><br><span class="line">smartpca -i &lt;file&gt;.ped -a &lt;file&gt;.pedsnp -b &lt;file&gt;.pedind -o &lt;file&gt;.pca -k 10 -p &lt;file&gt;.plot -e &lt;file&gt;.eval -l &lt;file&gt;.log</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p><strong>Visualization in R</strong></p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">plot(pca[,1],pca[,2],xlab = &quot;eigenvector1&quot;,ylab = &quot;eigenvector2&quot;)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li></ul><p>Here is an example:<br><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1200/1*oSOHZMoS-ZfmuAWiF8jY8Q.png" alt="An example"></p>]]></content>
    
    <summary type="html">
    
      &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Principal component analysis (PCA)&lt;/strong&gt; is a statistical procedure that uses an orthogonal transformation to convert a set of observations of possibly correlated variables (entities each of which takes on various numerical values) into a set of values of linearly uncorrelated variables called principal components.   &lt;/p&gt;
    
    </summary>
    
    
